<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-244-120  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 244 120.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 12 1990 v24 n11 p25(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Takeovers are not to blame. (corporate takeovers are notresponsible for computer industry decline) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Michel, Allen; Shaked, Israel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The era of corporate takeover is coming to an end because USCongress, banks and the media have all decided to view 'takeover'as a dirty word.andP;  Economists and business people suggest that therash of mergers, including those in the computer industry, wereconducted merely out of corporate greed for profits and argue thattime and money would be better spent on increasing productivity.andO;A study of 1987's top 200 business deals, according to 'BusinessWeek,' shows takeovers to be an important vehicle for increasingproductivity in US industries.andP;  Firms being taken over are thoseless profitable than their industry peers.andP;  Evidence indicatesthat takeovers revitalize industry laggards and that competitionrather than acquisition causes the demise of companies.andP;  Salvationfor many struggling companies lies in takeover by a stableorganization.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TakeoversCompaniesAnalysisProductivityCompetitionEconomics.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>